If you’ve ever opened LeetCode’s Daily Question, stared at it for ten minutes, and wished a magic button could at least give you a starting point — this post is for you. We’re going to break down, from the ground up, how you could build a browser extension that sits quietly in your Chrome toolbar, and when you click it, pops open a small panel that reads the current LeetCode problem and generates a solution for you.
This isn’t just “here’s some code” — it’s meant to teach you how browser extensions actually work, piece by piece, so you understand what’s happening at every step.
The User Experience We’re Designing
Before writing a single line of code, it helps to picture the flow exactly as the user experiences it:

• You’re on a LeetCode problem page (like leetcode.com/problems/sequential-digits).

• You click the extension icon in the Chrome toolbar.

• A small popup window appears.

• You click a “Solve” button inside that popup.

• A few seconds later, a solution appears — either in the popup or auto-typed into LeetCode’s code editor.
That’s the whole product, from the user’s point of view. Everything else is implementation detail.
The Core Pieces of Any Chrome Extension
Every Chrome extension is built from a handful of standard building blocks. Understanding these is 90% of understanding how our tool works.
1. manifest.json — the extension's ID card
This file tells Chrome what your extension is, what permissions it needs, and which files do what.
json
{
"manifest_version": 3,
"name": "LeetCode Daily Solver",
"version": "1.0",
"permissions": ["activeTab", "scripting", "storage"],
"host_permissions": ["https://leetcode.com/*"],
"action": {
"default_popup": "popup.html"
},
"content_scripts": [
{
"matches": ["https://leetcode.com/problems/*"],
"js": ["content.js"]
}
]
}Three things worth noticing:

• permissions tells Chrome what the extension is allowed to touch (here, the active tab and some local storage).

• action.default_popup is what opens when you click the toolbar icon.

• content_scripts is a script that automatically gets injected into any LeetCode problem page — this is how the extension can "see" the problem you're looking at.
2. The Popup (popup.html + popup.js)
This is the small window that appears when you click the icon. It’s really just a mini webpage — HTML, CSS, and JS — rendered in a fixed-size frame.
html
<!-- popup.html -->
<button id="solveBtn">Solve Today's Question</button>
<div id="output"></div>
<script src="popup.js"></script>js
// popup.js
document.getElementById("solveBtn").addEventListener("click", async () => {
const [tab] = await chrome.tabs.query({ active: true, currentWindow: true }); // Ask the content script (running on the LeetCode page) for the problem text
chrome.tabs.sendMessage(tab.id, { action: "getProblem" }, async (problem) => {
const solution = await solveWithAI(problem);
document.getElementById("output").innerText = solution;
});
});3. The Content Script (content.js) — the eyes on the page
This script runs inside the LeetCode page itself, meaning it can read the DOM — the problem title, description, constraints, and even the starter code template.
js
// content.js
chrome.runtime.onMessage.addListener((msg, sender, sendResponse) => {
if (msg.action === "getProblem") {
const title = document.querySelector("[data-cy='question-title']")?.innerText;
const description = document.querySelector(".description__text")?.innerText;
const starterCode = document.querySelector(".monaco-editor")?.innerText; sendResponse({ title, description, starterCode });
}
});This is the piece most people find “magical,” but it’s really just DOM scraping — reading text that’s already visible on your screen, the same way you would with your own eyes.
4. The AI Brain — turning a problem into a solution
Once we have the problem text, we need something that can actually reason through it and write code. This is where a call to a large language model API comes in — you send the problem description, and it returns a solution in your chosen language.
js
async function solveWithAI(problem) {
const response = await fetch("https://api.anthropic.com/v1/messages", {
method: "POST",
headers: { "Content-Type": "application/json" },
body: JSON.stringify({
model: "claude-sonnet-4-6",
max_tokens: 1000,
messages: [
{
role: "user",
content: `Solve this LeetCode problem in C++:\n\n${problem.title}\n\n${problem.description}\n\nStarter code:\n${problem.starterCode}`
}
]
})
}); const data = await response.json();
return data.content[0].text;
}The extension itself doesn’t “think” — it’s a courier. It gathers the problem text, hands it to the model, and displays whatever comes back.
5. (Optional) Auto-typing the answer into the editor
If you want the solution to appear directly inside LeetCode’s code editor instead of just the popup, the content script can programmatically insert text into the Monaco editor LeetCode uses. This is more advanced — Monaco has its own API, and just setting innerText won't work reliably — but conceptually it's the same idea: find the editor element, and dispatch the text into it.
Putting It All Together
Here’s the full round-trip, step by step:

• Click icon → Chrome opens popup.html.

• Click “Solve” → popup.js messages the content script running on the LeetCode tab.

• Content script scrapes the problem title, description, and starter code from the page’s DOM.

• That data travels back to popup.js, which sends it to an AI API.

• The API returns generated code, which gets displayed in the popup (or typed into the editor).
Nothing here is exotic — it’s message-passing between a popup and a content script, DOM reading, and one API call. That’s the entire architecture.
Tech Stack Summary
LayerTechnologyExtension shellChrome Extensions API (Manifest V3)Popup UIHTML, CSS, vanilla JSPage interactionContent scripts + DOM APIsCommunicationchrome.runtime / chrome.tabs messagingReasoning engineLLM API (e.g., ChatGPT or another model)Storage (optional)chrome.storage for saving past solutions/history
Why I Actually Built This
I want to be upfront about the motivation here, because it’s not “I wanted a shortcut.”
Anyone who’s spent time on LeetCode knows the open secret: a meaningful chunk of students aren’t solving problems, they’re pasting them into ChatGPT or Claude in another tab and typing the answer back in. The platform has no real way to tell the difference between a submission that came from genuine problem-solving and one that came from a copy-paste round trip. The “Daily Streak,” the leaderboard, the solved count — none of it distinguishes the two. That’s a real gap in the platform, and it quietly punishes the students who are doing the work honestly, because their effort doesn’t show up as any different from someone who spent thirty seconds copy-pasting.
Building this extension wasn’t about making that problem worse — it was about making it undeniable. If a browser extension with a few hundred lines of code can scrape a problem, hand it to a model, and paste back a working solution in seconds, that’s proof the current setup can’t actually tell who solved something and who didn’t. Once you can demonstrate a gap instead of just describing it, it’s a lot harder to ignore.
The other half of this project, honestly, is that I hadn’t shipped much before this. I wanted something concrete to point to that shows I can actually build — wire up a Chrome extension end to end, get a popup talking to a content script, handle async messaging, and integrate a real API — rather than just talking about skills on a resume. This project, unfinished as it is, does that. It’s a working proof of concept, not a polished product, and that’s fine: the goal was to prove the idea and prove I could build it, not to launch a tool for mass use.
If anything, the right next step for a project like this isn’t to hide it — it’s to push it further in the direction of exposing the gap: logging how fast a “solve” happens, comparing that against typical human solve times, and showing just how trivially the honor system breaks. That’s a more interesting (and more defensible) project than a silent cheat tool, and it’s the direction I’d take this in next.
